[The tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Italy is now 80 539 cases, including 8165 deaths, up from 74 386 cases and 7503 deaths reported on 25 Mar 2020. The 24-hour change between 25 and 26 Mar 2020 was 6153 newly confirmed cases, compared with 5210 newly confirmed cases between 24 and 25 Mar 2020. Cases continue to be concentrated in Lombardy (34 889), the epicenter of the outbreak, Emilia-Romagna (10 816), and Venice (6935), all in the northern part of the country. Those 3 provinces combined account for 61.7% of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Another active province is Piedmont with a total of 6534 cases and represents 8.3% of newly reported cases. There is an excellent interactive map at http://opendatadpc.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/b0c68bce2cce478eaac82fe38d4138b1 to visualize the caseloads per region in near real time.

On 9 Mar 2020, Italy announced a lockdown for the northern provinces where the outbreak was concentrated. On 10 Mar 2020, this was expanded to be countrywide. On 11 Mar 2020, Italy announced the closure of non-essential businesses. As for seeing an impact, one shouldn't expect to see an impact until at least one incubation period has passed, as there are newly infected individuals who are still in their incubation period for up to 14 days. That being said, hopefully the 27.0% decrease in reported cases over a 72 hour period was a sign of slowing down of transmission, and not of reporting variance, although there has been an increase over the past 2 days. As mentioned before, the Public Health world is looking at Italy to see if this lockdown is feasible and if it has an impact in terms of slowing down transmission of the virus.

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7149046,75. - Mod.MPP]

