[5] Democratic Republic of the Congo
Date: Thu 26 Mar 2020
Source: Ministry of Health Bulletin [in French, machine and Mod.MPP trans., abridged, edited]
https://mailchi.mp/bab0e0e40aa6/covid-19-bulletin-n1-du-24-mars-3898509?e=e838b4d57b


[A daily newsletter was produced by the Ministry of Health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo during the ebolavirus outbreak. Now that transmission of the ebolavirus has been interrupted (waiting for 2 incubation periods for announcement), the Ministry has been issuing the same platform bulletin daily in response to the COVID-19 outbreak.- Mod.MPP]

Epidemiological evolution of COVID-19 in the Democratic Republic of the Congo:

- Since the start of the epidemic declared on [10 Mar 2020], the cumulative total is 54 confirmed cases;
- in total, there were 4 deaths and 1 person recovered;
- 3 new confirmed cases, including 2 in Kinshasa and 1 in North Kivu (the origin of this case is under investigation);
- 1 new death from confirmed cases.

News

A new COVID-19 affected area in the DRC
---------------------------------------
- The Technical Secretary of the Multisectoral Committee for the Pandemic Response [CMR] to COVID-19, Prof Muyembe Ntamfum, announced in his communication on Thursday [26 Mar 2020], that a new area of the Democratic Republic of the Congo has been affected by the COVID-19 disease;
- it is the province of North Kivu in the east of this country. The origin of the case, he said, is still under investigation;
- he also raised awareness of the signs of COVID-19. To this end, Prof Muyembe reported that a patient with COVID-19 has signs or symptoms like sore throat, dry cough, cold, fever, headache, and difficult breathing;
- "these symptoms are not specific to COVID-19, because in our case, malaria and typhoid fever, 2 very common diseases, have the same picture. Only the consulting doctor or nurse can say whether or not this is a suspected COVID-19 case," he said;
- he thanked the Congolese people for their unconditional support for the COVID-19 response teams;
- in addition, this same Thursday [26 Mar 2020], UNICEF handed over to the CMR COVID-19 Technical Secretariat a large batch of communication and hygiene kits, including handwashes, soap, and some communication tools for awareness-raising on the COVID-19.

